This is an issue across industries. It's forcing us content professionals to develop new strategies to publish truly different and more valuable content.

attachments.title: Copycat Content: SEO Tools Got Us Here, Humans Will Get Us Out - Animalz
attachments.text: There’s a copycat crisis in content marketing. Explore the search results for virtually any lucrative keyword, and you’ll find a bunch of articles with lookalike titles, headers and examples. Increasingly, “SEO content” has become a synonym for meandering “ultimate guides” and formulaic “7 ways” listicles. Similarities between blog posts chasing the same keywords are unavoidable—there’s... Read more »

text: The solution, which I didn't get to launch and test/prove because of COVID-19 and being laid off, was to lean more into the customer community and use content as the proverbial campfire/water cooler for them to learn from one another vs the brand. Not only is the content more human, it's impossible to copy.

text: Another way to think about it without trying to find copy-proof content ideas is to focus on the sustainable strategic advantage of your content operation. What you and your competitors are publishing might be identical, but how you go about it might not be. The cost of producing net new content, for example, might be drastically lower than your competition and therefore give you a higher ROI.

text:
<@U010JU2GTND> I’ve been dealing with the same thing for the last couple of years - to the point that they’ve copied our proposal documents and attempted to get prospects to confuse our two brands, so I get you.

The only effective strategy that I’ve found is to do stuff they can’t copy — leverage the relationships we’ve built for content, create community, up our production value, find and really highlight our differentiator, showcase our people and process, let people have a more intimate look inside our org.

But I hear you, it’s still tough. Especially when you work so hard on something and they just steal it. For a while I was doing it right back to them, so anything they wrote, I’d write a piece that was 10x better then use our network to promote the crap out of it so it out ranked theirs. But it ultimately isn’t super sustainable and emotionally, it was a lot.

text:
+100 to <@UJ420S7MG>

If you have the bandwidth, build a dashboard that shows the URL, the keyword it ranks for, and the most recent rank position. If you have metrics for the value of the page/post/etc, that'll be useful, too. Monitor it monthly or quarterly. As posts slip in rank, review the content and identify how to refresh it. When you refresh it, change the date to the date you refreshed it.

Don't play their game of adding more text for search engines to crawl (turning 20 tips into 50, 100, 101, 132, etc).
